[Helen Branswell (https://twitter.com/HelenBranswell):
1. DRC reports a health care worker has contracted #Ebola. The person, who was vaccinated (no indication how long ago) is alive. DRC says there've been 165 HCW infections; 41 have died. @WHOAFRO puts the figure at 170.
3 cases Tue 14 Jan, no deaths. Totals: 3406 cases, 2236 deaths.

2. The North Kivu-Ituri #Ebola outbreak shows little sign of letting up though it looked like it might be ending in November 2019. The daily case increase is far lower than at the height of the outbreak (April-May 2019) but cases are accruing steadily in places where resistance persists; see figure in URL cited.]

- 13 Jan 2020. South Sudan NOT Ebola
[Radio Tamazui (abridged, edited)]
https://radiotamazuj.org/en/news/article/quarantined-patient-suspected-to-have-ebola-tests-negative

Quarantined patient suspected to have Ebola tests negative

A patient in Mapel area of Wau State who was quarantined amid fears he had Ebola does not have the killer virus, health officials have confirmed.

The unidentified patient was rushed to Mapel hospital on Fri [10 Jan 2020] with bleeding from ears, a sign of Ebola. He is a soldier undergoing military trainings in Mapel.

Health officials said Friday [10 Jan 2020] that while Ebola was unlikely, they could not rule out the virus until test results came back from the capital Juba.

Simon Athuai Akot, health minister in Wau State, told Radio Tamazuj this afternoon that the results showed that it was not a case of Ebola.
"The cases were 3, but laboratory tests have confirmed that the patients at the Mapel hospital are not suffering from Ebola," Athuai said.

"Samples had been taken for analysis by our Ebola taskforce and a team from World Health Organization, but laboratory tests showed that it was not a case of Ebola. One patient who was suspected to have Ebola was just found suffering from a respiratory disease," he added.

South Sudan has a porous border with the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), where many people move across the 2 countries for business and other activities.

South Sudan suffered an Ebola outbreak in 2004 after the World Health Organization (WHO) reported 20 cases including 5 deaths from Ebola hemorrhagic fever (EHF) in Yambio.

