- 15 Jan 2020. USA (Kentucky): Ebola suspected, but NOT Ebola
[Daily Star (abridged, edited)]
https://www.dailystar.co.uk/news/world-news/ebola-fears-hit-after-student-21282948

[Byline: Sophie Bateman]

US student quarantined with unidentified disease at Barbourville Appalachian Regional Healthcare Hospital -- rumours of Ebola. This student has never been out of the US; rumours denied.

Ebola fears hit the US after a student was quarantined with a mystery disease. Kentucky state officials are investigating after a student was put into isolation with a potentially infectious disease, frightening locals and sparking fears of the deadly Ebola virus.

Kentucky state officials are investigating the case at Barbourville Appalachian Regional Healthcare Hospital along with Centres for Disease Control and Prevention.

The patient is a student at Union College. University President Dr Marcia Hawkins has asked locals to keep them "in your prayers" but said there was no immediate risk to the public.

The case has prompted rumours on social media the student has contracted the Ebola virus, which is currently ravaging parts of Africa and killed more than 11 000 people in West Africa between 2013 and 2016.

Barbourville residents told local media they were shocked by the "very scary" disease in their community.

Dr Hawkins has denied the Ebola rumours, claiming the student has not travelled out of the country or come into contact with the virus.

The disease, which is reportedly not airborne, is still unknown. Health officials are carrying out tests to identify the virus.

Barbourville ARH Hospital is still open and is currently accepting patients as normal.

The Kentucky Department for Public Health is still assessing whether there's a threat to public health, but said the wider community is not believed to be at risk as "appropriate protocols were followed at the hospital to prevent exposure to other patients."

Anyone in Barbourville experiencing symptoms of a virus, including fever, nausea, body aches or lethargy, is encouraged to seek medical assistance immediately.

Ebola symptoms include fever, a sore threat, muscle pain and headaches. Those infected often experience vomiting, diarrhoea and a rash along with poor liver and kidney function. External and internal bleeding are also common.

The virus kills, on average, 50% of the people it infects.

